  "detailedRequirements": "<p><strong>SUMMARY</strong></p>\n\n<p>What&#39;s needed: An optimised version of our WebGL XRE receiver codebase.</p>\n\n<p><strong>OVERVIEW</strong></p>\n\n<p>XRE is a system that allows client / server communication and drawing based on commands from the server.&nbsp; The client can also send events, like key presses or mouse clicks, back to the server, and the server can respond with new drawing or other calls.&nbsp; Right now, the receiver is built with Javascript and the drawing is done using WebGL.</p>\n\n<p><strong>PROBLEM DESCRIPTION</strong></p>\n\n<p>We have a codebase that runs as an XRE receiver in a web browser with a suite of test cases being run.&nbsp; This works well, but now we need to optimise it as much as possible so it runs much faster.&nbsp; The initial drawing code and codebase was built years ago, before there were helpful tools for WebGL and before the WebGL standard was even implemented in most browsers.&nbsp; With the latest browsers and specifications, along with new helper libraries, we should be able to greatly increase the performance of the code in a modern browser.</p>\n\n<p><strong>CHALLENGE OBJECTIVE</strong></p>\n\n<p>The goal for this challenge is to optimize the codebase so that it runs quickly.&nbsp; Tests to look at include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>All tests under 4) XRE Animation Test Suite, particularly AnimationsTest, Painting Stress Test, and Performance Stress Test</li>\n\t<li>All tests under 2) Graphics Test Suite</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>OPTIMIZATIONS INCLUDE:</strong></p>\n\n<p>1. Caching as much as possible and reuse shaders and other elements wherever possible</p>\n\n<p>2. Only drawing what is in the bounds of the screen</p>\n\n<p>3. Aggressive drawing of only visible pixels - if something is behind another, opaque element, only the front pixels would be rendered.</p>\n\n<p>4. Better threading and JSON parsing</p>\n\n<p>5. Anything else you think would help. &nbsp;Use your imagination!</p>\n\n<p>6. Pixi.js usage (below)</p>\n\n<p>7. Enabling / disabling logging</p>\n\n<p>Google Chrome&rsquo;s profiling tool can help show where the majority of the CPU usage is.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><strong>PIXI.JS</strong></p>\n\n<p>The client has approved Pixi.js as a better drawing framework to use for the WebGL drawing done in the application.&nbsp; You can replace most or all of WebGl2DContext.js with calls to the Pixi.js library.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.pixijs.com\">http://www.pixijs.com���</a></p>\n\n<p><strong>REQUIREMENTS</strong></p>\n\n<p>You are free to change anything in the code, provided that the tests still run as they do now with the current codebase.</p>\n\n<p>To pass screening, your submission must show relatively substantial performance gains - in the 30-50% range.&nbsp; Submissions with superficial changes and only minor updates won&rsquo;t pass into review.</p>\n",
